(The use of alliteration in picturesque narrative is well illuStrated in this passage, in which fully half the verses show alliterative effects. The most conspicuous cases are in 338, 356, 358, 362, 364, 370, 371, 376, 378, 382. Anaphora is employed in 36:34 (per . . . per . . . per), 365-7 (auc tu . . . aut, tu), 367 (si qua . . . si quam).

Spondees are used 10 express solemnity in 352 and 363, and slow movement in 358 ; to heighten a climax in 361, and to suggest comfort after sorrow in 382.)
